## Goal

Understand the current state of the codebase as it relates to the requested change.
Do NOT propose solutions — only observe and report.

## Steps

1. Search memory for prior context on this topic:
   `memory_search(query="<change description>")`
2. Identify which files, modules, and directories are relevant to this change
3. Read the most relevant files — focus on interfaces, not implementation details
4. Note: existing patterns, naming conventions, dependencies, test coverage, edge cases, known risks
5. Save findings to memory:
   - title: `SDD Explore: <change_id>`
   - topic_key: `sdd-<change_id>-context`
   - type: `context`
   - content (structured):
     ```
     ## Relevant Files
     <file paths and their role>

     ## Key Patterns
     <naming, structure, conventions observed>

     ## Dependencies
     <what this change depends on or affects>

     ## Test Coverage
     <existing tests relevant to this change>

     ## Risks
     <potential pitfalls, breaking changes>
     ```

## Output

A structured context document saved to memory. Write no source code.

## Board Update

**After saving to memory**, update the project board. Check your prompt for an issue number (look for `for issue #N` or `#<number>`). If found, execute the commands below with `<ISSUE_NUMBER>` replaced by that number. **If no issue number is present in your prompt, skip this entire section.**

```bash
ITEM_ID=$(gh api graphql -f query='query{organization(login:"reverberage"){projectV2(number:2){items(first:100){nodes{id content{...on Issue{number}}}}}}}' --jq '.data.organization.projectV2.items.nodes[] | select(.content.number == <ISSUE_NUMBER>) | .id')
[ -n "$ITEM_ID" ] && gh project item-edit --id "$ITEM_ID" --field-id PVTSSF_lADOEeFGTc4Bc5CtzhXejII --project-id PVT_kwDOEeFGTc4Bc5Ct --single-select-option-id 47fc9ee4
[ -n "$ITEM_ID" ] && gh project item-edit --id "$ITEM_ID" --field-id PVTSSF_lADOEeFGTc4Bc5CtzhYUpaI --project-id PVT_kwDOEeFGTc4Bc5Ct --single-select-option-id cbe57d4d
```
